Digital Stopwatch using 8051 Microcontroller

This project is a simple digital stopwatch built using the 8051 microcontroller and simulated in Keil µVision. The main idea was to understand how timers and interrupts work in real embedded systems by implementing a practical application.

The stopwatch can start, stop, reset, and even store lap time. Timer0 is used to generate a 1 millisecond delay, which is then used to count seconds accurately. All the controls are handled through port pins, making the design straightforward and easy to follow.

What this project does

* Start and stop the timer
* Reset the stopwatch
* Record lap time
* Keep accurate time using interrupts

What I used

* AT89C51 (8051 microcontroller)
* Embedded C
* Keil µVision for simulation

Why this project matters

This project helped me understand how microcontroller timers work, how interrupts improve efficiency, and how real-time systems are designed. It’s a good beginner-level project for anyone learning embedded systems.

Where it can be used

* Basic timing applications
* Learning embedded programming
* Simple digital clock or timer systems

Overall, this project is a hands-on way to learn core concepts like timers, interrupts, and microcontroller programming.
